description: Two New York City subway work trains collided on Wednesday morning. Five people were on board the trains and one worker is being treated for non-life-threatening injuries.
text:
Two New York City subway work trains collided in a tunnel early Wednesday morning, injuring one person.
The Metropolitan Transportation Authority says the trains 'bumped into each other' but didn't derail at about 5am.
One train was stationary and the other was moving at the time of the collision.
Scroll down for video
Two New York City subway work trains collided in a tunnel early Wednesday morning, injuring one person
The Metropolitan Transportation Authority says the trains 'bumped into each other' but didn't derail at about 5am
The agency says one MTA worker is being treated for non-life-threatening injuries.
There were no passengers on the trains, and MTA officials say the accident had no impact on subway service during the morning commute.
Five people were on board the trains at the time of the crash.
The trains collided in the 53rd Street tunnel that carries passenger trains between Manhattan and Queens (file photo)
Fire department officials say firefighters removed one person from the Manhattan side of a tunnel under the East River after the accident occurred around 5.10am.
The trains collided in the 53rd Street tunnel that carries passenger trains between Manhattan and Queens.
That stretch of tunnel near the Queens Plaza E and M train stop has been undergoing repairs.
